SIMPLE: enter
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Enter-
<hw>En"ter-</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <ety>[F. <ets>entre</ets> between, fr. L.
<ets>inter</ets>. See <er>Inter-</er>]</ety> <def>A prefix signifying
<xex>between</xex>, <xex>among</xex>, <xex>part</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Enter</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Enter
<hw>En"ter</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Entered</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Entering</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>entren</ets>,
<ets>enteren</ets>, F. <ets>entrer</ets>, fr. L. <ets>intrare</ets>, fr.
<ets>intro</ets> inward, contr. fr. <ets>intero</ets> (sc.
<ets>loco</ets>), fr. <ets>inter</ets> in between, between. See
<er>Inter-</er>, <er>In</er>, and cf. <er>Interior</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To come or go into; to pass into the interior of; to
pass within the outer cover or shell of; to penetrate; to pierce;
<as>as, to <ex>enter</ex> a house, a closet, a country, a door, etc.;
the river <ex>enters</ex> the sea.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That darksome cave they <qex>enter</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I, . . . with the multitude of my redeemed,⟦br⟧
Shall <qex>enter</qex> heaven, long absent.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To unite in; to join; to be admitted to; to become a
member of; <as>as, to <ex>enter</ex> an association, a college, an
army</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To engage in; to become occupied with; <as>as, to
<ex>enter</ex> the legal profession, the book trade, etc.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To pass within the limits of; to attain; to begin;
to commence upon; <as>as, to <ex>enter</ex> one's teens, a new era, a
new dispensation</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To cause to go (into), or to be received (into); to
put in; to insert; to cause to be admitted; <as>as, to <ex>enter</ex> a
knife into a piece of wood, a wedge into a log; to <ex>enter</ex> a boy
at college, a horse for a race, etc.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To inscribe; to enroll; to record; <as>as, to
<ex>enter</ex> a name, or a date, in a book, or a book in a catalogue;
to <ex>enter</ex> the particulars of a sale in an account, a manifest of
a ship or of merchandise at the customhouse.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>To go into or upon, as
lands, and take actual possession of them.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>To
place in regular form before the court, usually in writing; to put upon
record in proper from and order; <as>as, to <ex>enter</ex> a writ,
appearance, rule, or judgment</as>.</def> <rj><au>Burrill.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>To make report of (a vessel or her cargo) at the
customhouse; to submit a statement of (imported goods), with the
original invoices, to the proper officer of the customs for estimating
the duties. See <er>Entry</er>, 4.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>To file or inscribe upon the records of the land
office the required particulars concerning (a quantity of public land)
in order to entitle a person to a right of pre⟦eum⟧mption.</def>
<mark>[U.S.]</mark> <rj><au>Abbott.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <def>To deposit for copyright the title or description
of (a book, picture, map, etc.); <as>as, ⟦ldquo⟧<ex>entered</ex>
according to act of Congress</as>.⟦rdquo⟧</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>11.</sn> <def>To initiate; to introduce favorably.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Enter</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Enter
<hw>En"ter</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To go or come in; --
often with <xex>in</xex> used pleonastically; also, to begin; to take
the first steps.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The year <xex>entering</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Evelyn.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>No evil thing approach nor <qex>enter</qex> in.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Truth is fallen in the street, and equity can not
<qex>enter</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Is. lix. 14.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>For we which have believed do <qex>enter</qex> into rest.</q>
<rj><qau>Heb. iv. 3.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To get admission; to introduce one's self; to
penetrate; to form or constitute a part; to become a partaker or
participant; to share; to engage; -- usually with <xex>into</xex>;
sometimes with <xex>on</xex> or <xex>upon</xex>; <as>as, a ball
<ex>enters</ex> into the body; water <ex>enters</ex> into a ship; he
<ex>enters</ex> into the plan; to <ex>enter</ex> into a quarrel; a
merchant <ex>enters</ex> into partnership with some one; to
<ex>enter</ex> upon another's land; the boy <ex>enters</ex> on his tenth
year; to <ex>enter</ex> upon a task; lead <ex>enters</ex> into the
composition of pewter.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To penetrate mentally; to consider attentively; --
with <xex>into</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He is particularly pleased with . . . Sallust for his
<qex>entering</qex> into internal principles of action.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Enteradenography</ent>⟦br⟧
